3) Conclusion — why I chose the live Tokyo Tapes‑style recording and rejected the Whitney compilation
- The Tokyo Tapes‑style live disc aligns strongly with multiple explicit preferences: organic, minimally overdubbed sound; emotive, unvarnished vocals; prominent, expressive guitar; natural room ambience and roomy mixes; tactile mastering and coherent sequencing that reward repeat focused listens. Those concrete production and sequencing qualities are central to my stated taste.
- The Whitney Houston "Best Of" is a polished pop hits compilation that embodies many of the things I said I avoid (heavy studio polish, multi‑tracking, singles‑first sequencing, radio/mastering choices oriented to instant hooks). Even though the vocals are excellent, the compilation’s production and format put it at odds with my core preferences for intimate, atmospheric, album‑focused listening experiences.
- Therefore the live Tokyo Tapes‑style recording is the clear fit: it satisfies the acoustic/ambient/production characteristics I seek and avoids the overproduced, hits‑oriented traits that the Whitney compilation represents.

